    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>To Avoid an Accident</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Ricardo Gomez on Robert H Frank's May 16 Op-Ed on sport utility vehicles; says smaller, more maneuverable vehicle might more easily escape accident</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is not surprising to learn that, as Robert H. Frank points out (Op-Ed, May 16), being inside a heavier vehicle increases the probability of walking away from an accident unhurt. But how often does a hard maneuver turn into an accident precisely because the vehicle involved is so heavy?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>It is not surprising to learn that, as Robert H. Frank points out (Op-Ed, May 16), being inside a heavier vehicle increases the probability of walking away from an accident unhurt. But how often does a hard maneuver turn into an accident precisely because the vehicle involved is so heavy?</p>
        <p>Intuition suggests that a smaller, more maneuverable vehicle might more easily escape an accident. After all, the best accident is not the one in which the other guy gets more serious injuries, but the one that does not happen.</p>
        <p>RICARDO  GOMEZ  New Brunswick, N.J., May 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
